{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01DgVcyd713S555PKi37KVKe","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Both goal conditions are met. TLS is now enabled on the CockroachDB cluster.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe `cockroachdb` cluster was running in insecure mode and is now secured with TLS.\n\n**What I did:**\n\n1. **Generated certificates** using the `cockroach cert` tooling inside `crdb-cluster-0`:\n   - CA cert (`ca.crt`)\n   - Node cert/key with SANs covering all pod, headless, and public service DNS names (`*.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local`, `crdb-cluster-public`, `localhost`, etc.)\n   - Root client cert/key (`client.root.crt/key`)\n\n2. **Stored them** in a Kubernetes secret `crdb-certs`, mounted into the StatefulSet at `/cockroach/cockroach-certs` with `defaultMode: 0400` (CockroachDB rejects world/group-readable key files).\n\n3. **Patched the StatefulSet** to:\n   - Replace `--insecure` with `--certs-dir=/cockroach/cockroach-certs` in the start command\n   - Switch the liveness/readiness probe scheme from `HTTP` → `HTTPS` (the admin/health endpoint serves TLS in secure mode, so probes would otherwise fail)\n\n4. **Rolled the pods.** The rolling update stalled mid-way (a secure pod-2 couldn't form quorum with the still-insecure pods 0/1 — a known insecure→secure transition deadlock), so I deleted pods 0 and 1 to bring them onto the secure revision. All 3 pods then formed a healthy secure cluster.\n\n**Verification:**\n- Insecure access is **rejected**: `node is running secure mode, SSL connection required`\n- Secure access **succeeds**: `SELECT 1;` returns `1` via `--certs-dir=/cockroach/cockroach-certs`"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":329,"cache_creation_input_tokens":440,"cache_read_input_tokens":45758,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":440},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":